Project Report: Global Happiness Analysis

Introduction

Goal of the Analysis

In this project we investigated what are the main drivers of happiness across countries and regions. We hypothesized that the following factors may have a significant effect on nation's happiness level:

  • Economic well being,
  • Education,
  • Internet propogation,
  • Life expectency.

We used these variables to analyse their relationship with the overall happiness level across different countries.

Data Processing

In this section, our primary goal was to retain as much data as possible because it would make our analysis more objective.

Structure of the data processing:
$ \downarrow $ We first loaded the data and focused only on Year 2019, to keep our analysis sharp.
$ \downarrow $ Then we normalized the data by standartizing the labels in the datasets.
$ \downarrow $ After this we cleaned the data. We filled in some of the missing values using relavant sources.
$ \downarrow $ For the "Education expenditure" column, we used KNN-imputing algorithm to extrapolate and fill the missing data values.
Finally, we merged all the datasets. We successfully managed to keep all the 156 rows in the final dataframe.

Problem: Mismatching labels

We noticed that there are mismatching labels for countries and regions.
For example, in the dataset hap the country Russia is labeled as "Russia",
but in the dataset gdp it is labeled as "Russian Federation".

This is a problem because if we left-merged all the data right away, we would have a lot of 'NaN' values or duplicates.
(credits for this observation and for its solution: Aslbek).

We need to label countries with consistent naming.
To do this, we chose labels in the dataset gdp as the base labels, then we renamed mismathcing countries in other datasets.

Solution: Label correction

To resolve this problem, we found all the countries that have different labels.
To do this, we used type 'set' to easily find such differences.

Note: Why set? When we take the difference between sets e.g: set1 - set2,
it returns elements of set2 that are not present in set1.

This way, we find all the labels that need to be changed.

In[7]:

# ================================
# Correcting the labels
# ================================

# Define a dictionary with keys as "inconsistent" labels and values as "more universal" labels:
# e.g. 'Kyrgyzstan': 'Kyrgyz Republic',

name_corrections = {
    'Kyrgyzstan': 'Kyrgyz Republic',
	'Congo (Brazzaville)': 'Congo, Rep.',
	'Congo (Kinshasa)': 'Congo, Dem. Rep.',
	'Czech Republic': 'Czechia',
	'Egypt': 'Egypt, Arab Rep.',
	'Gambia': 'Gambia, The',
	'Hong Kong': 'Hong Kong SAR, China',
	'Iran': 'Iran, Islamic Rep.',
	'Northern Cyprus': 'Northern Mariana Islands',
	'Palestinian Territories': 'West Bank and Gaza',
	'Russia': 'Russian Federation',
	'Slovakia': 'Slovak Republic',
	'Somalia': 'Somalia, Fed. Rep.',
	'South Korea': 'Korea, Rep.',
	'Syria': 'Syrian Arab Republic',
	'Trinidad & Tobago': 'Trinidad and Tobago',
	'Turkey': 'Turkiye',
	'Venezuela': 'Venezuela, RB',
	'Vietnam': 'Viet Nam',
	'Yemen': 'Yemen, Rep.',
	'Ivory Coast': 'Cote d\'Ivoire',
	'Laos': 'Lao PDR',
	'Swaziland': 'Eswatini',
}

# We change labels of the datasets using the name_corrections dictionary:
# e.g. 'Kyrgyzstan' --> 'Kyrgyz Republic'
hap['Country'] = hap['Country'].replace(name_corrections)
edu['Country'] = edu['Country'].replace(name_corrections)
exp['Country'] = exp['Country'].replace(name_corrections)

Now that we have consistent labels, we can left-merge all the datasets.

Note: the new data set df_raw (see below) has exactly 156 rows, which means that no country was left out.
However, we called this dataset 'raw' because it still has missing values, which will be addressed in the next subsection.

Data Cleaning

In this subsection, we clean the main dataframe df_raw. We used three strategies to address the missing values while trying to keep bias low:

  1. We used historical imputation
  2. We used external data
  3. KNN imputation

In order to clean the data we first printed how many missing values there are.

Historical imputation

We looked back at the original datasets, and filled in some missing values with values from previous years.
For example, the country South Sudan had a missing "GDP per capita" field for 2019. We filled it in with "GDP per capita" field from 2015.
To reduce the error, we filled only those missing fields that had reasonably recent available 'filler' fields.
Historical imputation ensures that all the data were consistent and used the same metrics.

In[11]:
# ================================
# Filling in the missing GDP per capita data with recent years
# ================================
gdp_filling = {
    'Venezuela, RB': 15943.61,      # from 2014
    'Yemen, Rep.': 633.89,          # from 2018
    'South Sudan': 1080.15,         # from 2015
    'Taiwan': 36000                 # IMF estimate
}

for k, v in gdp_filling.items():
    df_raw.loc[df_raw['Country'] == k, 'GDP per capita'] = v

To fill in other missing values we used external data sources.
To reduce bias, we used data from the same sources.

KNN imputation algorithm

A big problem for us was the "Education expenditure" fields, because it was difficult to find sources that would measure the education expenditure in the same metrics.
Since the number of these missing fields was significant, we decided to not to dropping but to extrapolate them.
In order to do so, we used K-Nearest-Neighborhood imputing algorithm.

The algorithm finds the K nearest neighbors that are most similar to the country with missing data based on other factors (GDP, Life Expectancy, etc).
It then "predicts" the missing "Education expenditure" values, by taking a weighted average of these nearest neighbors. (weights were chosen as 'closeness')

This allowed us to make reasonably good guesses on a lot of missing values.

In[13]:
# ================================
# KNN Model extrapolation 
# ================================
features = df_raw.drop(columns=['Country'])                         # We drop the string column 'Country'

imputer = KNNImputer(n_neighbors=5, weights='distance')             # Look at the 5 closest neighbors. 
                                                                    # Note: we define weights as 'distance'
imputed_arr = imputer.fit_transform(features)                       # This line fills in the missing numbers but returns an array with no column names

imputed = pd.DataFrame(imputed_arr, columns=features.columns)       # We convert the array back to a dataframe to retrieve the column names               

imputed['Country'] = df_raw['Country']                              # This line is here to make sure every row has an appropriate country field

df_raw['Education expenditure'] = imputed['Education expenditure']  # We take the newly filled 'Education expenditure' column and put it back into our main dataframe

Final dataframe

We sorted the obtained final dataframe by "Happiness score" column in descending order. It makes the further analysis easier. Forexample, it sets us up for printing the top and bottom 10 countries. We also called it df as it will be our main dataframe that we will manipulate the most with. At the end we made a final check for any missing values, and indeed we managed to keep all the rows, however we will recall that our attempt for comprehensiveness will might've costed us some degree of error.

Data Visualization

Now that our data is clean, we move to the next section. We explore the main dataframe visually to idenify any patterns, outliers and evaluating the significance of features.

Structure of the data visualization:
$ \downarrow $ We will first have a 'high-level' look at the data disribution: we print the general statistics information (such as mean and standard deviation), top 10 and bottom 10 countries.
$ \downarrow $ Then, we build the correlation matrix to identify which variables move together.
$ \downarrow $ After this, we model using linear regression and polynomial regression models, we also included logarithmic regression. We evaluate those models using MSE metric.
$ \downarrow $ We determine which factors are the strongest preictors of the happiness level in a country.
Finally, we use these models to derive some insights.

General statistics

First, we look at the raw numbers. We identified the 'happiest' and 'least happy' nations to understand the range of our data.
We observe the following:

  • Global Mean: The average happiness score for the world is 5.41.
  • Standard Deviation: The standard deviation is 1.11.

Interpretation:
This standard deviation indicates a moderate spread in global well-being.
It means that while the "average" country has a score of 5.4, the majority of the world's nations fall comfortably between 4.3 and 6.5.
Scores significantly outside this rangesuch as Finland (>7.5) or South Sudan (<3.0)represent distinct outliers at the extreme ends of the spectrum.

By examining the tables below, we found the outliers at both ends of the scale:
The Happiest Countries:

  • Finland (7.769)
  • Denmark (7.600)
  • Norway (7.554)

The Least Happy Countries:

  • South Sudan (2.853)
  • Central African Republic (3.083)
  • Afghanistan (3.203)

Observations from the Correlation Matrix

Based on the heatmap and correlation coefficients, we can draw several key conclusions regarding the factors that influence a nation's happiness.

  1. The Most Significant Features (Strong Positive Correlation) The following factors showed the strongest relationship with the Happiness Score (Coefficient > 0.7):
  • Economic Health: GDP per capita (0.74) is a top predictor. This confirms the intuitive assumption that economic stability is a foundational requirement for national happiness.
  • Health & Longevity: Healthy life expectancy and Life expectancy (0.75) are nearly tied with GDP. Living a long, healthy life is just as important as being wealthy.
  • Connectivity: Surprisingly, Internet Users (% of Pop) (0.78) has a higher correlation than even GDP per capita. This suggests that access to information and digital infrastructure is a massive proxy for a country's development and well-being.
  • Social Stability: Social support (0.78) is also a top-tier predictor, reinforcing the idea that community safety nets are essential.
  1. The Least Significant Features (Weak Correlation)
  • Generosity: With a coefficient of only 0.076, Generosity has almost zero linear correlation with a nation's happiness score. This was a counter-intuitive finding, suggesting that a culture of donation does not necessarily translate to overall national satisfaction in this dataset.
  • Perceptions of Corruption: (0.39). While relevant, it is far less significant than economic or health factors.
  • Education Expenditure: (0.42). The correlation is moderate. This might indicate that how money is spent on education matters more than the raw amount spent.

Selection for Further Analysis

While Internet Users and Life Expectancy are strong predictors, they often act as proxies for a wealthy economy (high multicollinearity).

For our detailed Single Feature Linear Regression analysis in the next section, we have chosen GDP per capita as our primary independent variable. We selected it because:

  1. It is a "hard" statistic (measured in dollars) rather than a subjective survey score.
  2. It shows a strong, consistent correlation (0.74) with happiness.
  3. It allows us to clearly observe the economic disparities between the "happiest" and "least happy" nations.

Polynomial Regression Analysis

To find the best mathematical fit for our data, we tested four different degrees of polynomial regression:

  1. Linear (Degree 1): A straight line.
  2. Quadratic (Degree 2): A curve (parabola).
  3. Cubic (Degree 3): A more complex curve.
  4. Quartic (Degree 4): Highly flexible.

Methodology:

  • We split the data into Training (80%) and Testing (20%) sets.
  • We calculated the MSE (Mean Squared Error) for each model. Lower MSE indicates a better fit.

# ==========================================

X_reshaped = X_CONST.values.reshape(-1, 1)                  # Prepare the data. Sklearn requires a 2D array (matrix) for X, not a 1D list.

Logarithmic Regression (credits for the hypothesis and implementation: "Olzhas")

Observation

During our analysis, we noticed that the relationship between GDP and Happiness isn't strictly linear.

  • At low income levels, a small increase in money leads to a huge jump in happiness.
  • At high income levels, adding more money has a progressively smaller effect on well-being.

The Hypothesis

This pattern follows a logarithmic distribution. In economic theory, this is often referred to as "The Law of Diminishing Returns" or the "Catch-up Effect". Therefore, we hypothesized that fitting a regression to the natural logarithm of GDP would yield a better error score (MSE) than standard linear or polynomial models.

The mathematical formula for this model is:

$$\text{Happiness} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \ln(\text{GDP})$$

Where:

  • $\beta_0$ is the intercept (the baseline happiness).
  • $\beta_1$ is the coefficient that determines the steepness of the curve (how much happiness grows with logarithmic wealth).

Logarithmic scaling

We hypothesized that the relationship between Wealth and Happiness follows a logarithmic trend.

To test this visually, we plotted the data again but changed the X-axis to a logarithmic scale.

  • Hypothesis: If the relationship is truly logarithmic, the curved scatter plot should appear as a straight line on the scaled graph.

Formula for MSE (Log-Scaled Model): To quantify how well this "straight line" fits the transformed data, we use the Mean Squared Error (MSE).
In this specific context, the prediction is based on the logarithm of GDP:

$$\text{MSE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - (\beta_0 + \beta_1 \ln(x_i)))^2$$

Where:

  • $y_i$ is the actual Happiness Score.
  • $\ln(x_i)$ is the natural logarithm of the GDP.
  • $\beta_0$ and $\beta_1$ are the intercept and slope found by the linear regression.
In[22]:
# ==========================================
# Logarithmic Regression
# ==========================================

X = X_CONST.values.reshape(-1, 1)                 # Prepare Data
y = Y_CONST.values

mask = X.flatten() > 0                            # Masking out any possible negative or zero terms
X_clean = X[mask]                                 # This is rather redundant as the datasets don't have non-positive values
y_clean = y[mask]                                 # However this helped us at the development stage, when we worked in parallel with data processing stage

X_log = np.log(X_clean)                           # Log-transforming the x-axis
model = LinearRegression()                        # Building the linear regression model
model.fit(X_log, y_clean)                         # Fitting the model

y_pred = model.predict(X_log)                     # Calculate the evaluation metrics
mse_log = mean_squared_error(y_clean, y_pred)     # We use MSE again


print(f"Logarithmic Regression MSE: {mse_log:.4f}")
print(f"Equation: Happiness = {model.coef_[0]:.2f} * ln(GDP) + {model.intercept_:.2f}")

Reverting the Model

The line indeed looks linear! We revert the scale back to the original format using the derived formula:

$$y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \ln(x)$$

We calculate the MSE (standard, non-scaled) value again using the standard formula:

$$MSE = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{\text{actual}} - y_{\text{predicted}})^2$$

This formula is the conventional and statistically valid metric for evaluating regression models.
Even though we transformed the X-axis (GDP) to fit the curve, the Target Variable ($y$ or Happiness) remained in its original scale.
Therefore, calculating the sum of squared differences (error) between the actual happiness and predicted happiness
gives us a direct, "apples-to-apples" comparison with our previous polynomial models.

Results Regression Analysis

Based on the charts and regression results, here are the key conclusions derived from the analysis:

Money Matters, but with Diminishing Returns

The most obvious trend across all charts is a strong positive correlation: wealthier countries generally report higher happiness scores.

  • The "Saturation" Effect: The relationship is non-linear. The steepest increase in happiness happens when moving from low income to middle income (roughly US0 to US20,000 GDP per capita).
  • Plateauing: Beyond roughly US50,000, the curve flattens out significantly. This suggests that while basic economic stability is crucial for happiness, extreme wealth yields progressively smaller gains in well-being.

Model Performance: Linear vs. Polynomial

  • Linear (Degree 1) is Too Simple: The straight line (MSE: 0.507) is the worst fit. It underestimates happiness in poor nations and overestimates it in very rich ones, failing to capture the "curved" reality of the data.
  • Degree 2 & 3 are the "Sweet Spot": The quadratic (Degree 2, MSE: 0.405) and cubic (Degree 3, MSE: 0.374) models fit the data much better, effectively capturing the rapid rise and subsequent leveling off.
  • Degree 4 is Overfitting: The Degree 4 model (MSE: 0.465) actually performs worse than Degree 3. As seen in the charts, the curve hooks upwards aggressively at the far right. This is a classic case of the model "hallucinating" a trend based on a few outliers rather than capturing a real economic rule.

Logarithmic Regression is Likely the "True" Fit

  • The Logarithmic Regression (MSE: 0.364) has the lowest error of the simple models and ties closely with the complex polynomials.
  • The chart showing the "Log Scale" (where the x-axis is compressed) reveals a near-perfect straight line.
  • Economic Interpretation: This supports the theory of Marginal Utility (or the Weber-Fechner law). It implies that happiness doesn't go up with every dollar added, but rather with every multiplication of income (i.e., Going from US10k to US20k feels the same as going from US40k to US80k).

Variance Remains (Money Isn't Everything)

  • Even with the best-fitting line, there is significant "scatter" or variance. For example, at the US40,000 GDP mark, happiness scores range widely between roughly 5.5 and 7.5.
  • This proves that while GDP is a massive predictor, it is not the only factor. Variables like social support, freedom, and health likely account for the vertical distance between a dot and the regression line.

Feature Significance Analysis (Standardized Regression)

Introduction

While the correlation matrix tells us how each variable relates to happiness individually, it does not tell us which factors are the most important drivers when all variables are interacting simultaneously. For example, GDP and Life Expectancy are often highly correlated with each other; determining which one actually "causes" the increase in happiness requires a more advanced approach.

To solve this, we performed a Standardized Multivariate Linear Regression.

  • The Challenge: Our data uses vastly different units (e.g., GDP in thousands of dollars vs. Freedom as a 0-1 score). Comparing their raw regression coefficients would be misleading.
  • The Solution: We applied StandardScaler to normalize all features to the same scale (Mean = 0, Standard Deviation = 1). This creates a "common currency," allowing us to directly compare the magnitude of each feature's impact on the target variable.
In[24]:

print(f"Mean Squared Error: {mse:.3f}")

# Extract Feature Importance
coefficients = pd.DataFrame({
    "Feature": X.columns,
    "Coefficient": lr.coef_
}).sort_values("Coefficient", ascending=False)

print("\nStandardized Feature Importance:")
coefficients

Results of the Analysis

The standardized regression model achieved an $R^2$ score of 0.640, indicating that these features can explain roughly 64% of the variance in global happiness.

By ranking the standardized coefficients, we arrived at the following conclusions about what truly drives well-being:

  1. Community Over Capital: The single most powerful predictor of a nation's happiness is Social Support (0.358). This surpasses even economic factors, suggesting that a population's sense of having someone to rely on is the foundational bedrock of national well-being.

  2. The "Big Three" Pillars: Following Social Support, the next most critical factors are GDP per Capita (0.289) and Freedom to make life choices (0.237). Together with Social Support, these three variables form the primary tier of influence.

  3. The Digital Proxy: Internet Users (0.218) remains a significant predictor. In this model, internet access likely acts as a strong proxy for a country's modern infrastructure and access to information, capturing development aspects that GDP alone might miss.

  4. Factors with Low Marginal Impact: Once the major factors (Money, Community, Freedom) are accounted for, variables like Generosity (0.022) and Perceptions of Corruption (-0.023) have a surprisingly negligible impact on the final score. This implies that while corruption is negative, its effect is easily overshadowed by the presence of strong positive factors like social support.

Clusters

To identify distinct "global tiers" of development, we applied an unsupervised machine learning technique called K-Means Clustering. Unlike the regression analysis, which predicts a specific score, clustering allows us to uncover natural groupings in the data based on shared characteristics.

1. Determination of Optimal Clusters ($K=3$)

Before running the final model, we utilized the Elbow Method to determine the optimal number of groups. By calculating the "Inertia" (sum of squared distances within clusters) for range $K=1$ to $K=10$, we observed a sharp "elbow" at $K=3$.

  • Interpretation: This suggests that the world's nations naturally fall into three distinct categories (roughly corresponding to Underdeveloped, Developing, and Developed nations). Adding more clusters beyond 3 yields diminishing returns in model precision.

2. The Model

We trained the K-Means algorithm ($K=3$) on the standardized feature set.

  • Note on Dimensions: While the scatter plots below visualize these clusters using only two dimensions (GDP per Capita vs. Happiness Score) for clarity, the algorithm actually segmented the countries using all available numerical features (including Social Support, Freedom, and Life Expectancy).

3. Cluster Centroids (The "Average" Country)

The table below displays the Centroidsthe mathematical center of each cluster. These values represent the "average profile" of a country belonging to that group.

Feature Cluster 1 (Low) Cluster 2 (Mid) Cluster 0 (High)
Avg. Happiness Score 4.36 5.82 7.02
Avg. GDP per Capita ($) $2,066 $14,286 $56,209
Social Support 0.93 1.37 1.49
Freedom to make choices 0.32 0.40 0.55
Healthy Life Expectancy (Low) (Mid) (High)

Cluster Descriptions:

  • Cluster 1 (The "Struggling" Nations): Characterized by very low GDP (~$2k) and significant deficits in social support (0.93). These nations struggle to convert what little wealth they have into happiness.
  • Cluster 2 (The "Emerging" Middle): This is the transition zone. With a GDP (~$14k) roughly 7x higher than the bottom cluster, they achieve a massive jump in happiness (+1.5 points), showing the high marginal utility of income at this stage.
  • Cluster 0 (The "Thriving" Elite): The wealthiest nations. Despite having 4x the GDP of Cluster 2 (\$56k vs \$14k), the happiness gain is smaller (+1.2 points), illustrating the "diminishing returns" of extreme wealth.
In[27]:
# ==========================================
# Prepare Data for Clustering
# ==========================================
# We select the features that define a country's status + outcome
features_for_clustering = [
    'Happiness score', 
    'GDP per capita', 
    'Social support',  
    'Freedom to make life choices', 
    'Generosity', 
    'Perceptions of corruption'
]

# Create the subset
X_cluster = df[features_for_clustering].copy()

# SCALE THE DATA (Crucial!)
scaler_cluster = StandardScaler()
X_cluster_scaled = scaler_cluster.fit_transform(X_cluster)

# ==========================================
# The Elbow Method Loop
# ==========================================
inertia = []
k_range = range(1, 11)

for k in k_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10) # n_init suppresses warnings
    kmeans.fit(X_cluster_scaled)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# ==========================================
# Plotting the Elbow
# ==========================================
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
plt.plot(k_range, inertia, marker='o', linestyle='--', color='purple')
plt.title('Elbow Method: Optimal Number of Clusters')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Inertia (Variance)')
plt.grid(True)
plt.xticks(k_range)
plt.show()

Determination of Optimal Clusters ($K=3$)

To determine the most natural grouping of countries, we utilized the Elbow Method, which tracks the "Inertia" (sum of squared distances within clusters) as we increase the number of groups.

Why we chose $K=3$:

  • The "Elbow" Point: As observed in the chart, the inertia drops dramatically when moving from 1 to 2 clusters, and again significantly from 2 to 3.
  • Diminishing Returns: After $K=3$, the curve begins to flatten (or "bend"). Adding a 4th or 5th cluster yields only marginal improvements in model tightness while making the interpretation more complex.
  • Interpretability: Statistically, $K=3$ represents the "sweet spot" where we maximize the distinction between groups without over-fragmenting the data. In the context of global development, this likely corresponds to three distinct tiers: Underdeveloped, Developing, and Highly Developed nations.

Results for the Clustering Analysis

Using K-Means clustering ($K=3$), the algorithm successfully segmented the dataset into three distinct global tiers. The visualization reveals a clear trajectory of development, with countries grouped not just by geography, but by shared socioeconomic realities.

1. Cluster 1: The "Struggling" Nations (Orange)

  • Profile: Low Income (roughly $2,066 avg GDP) & Low Happiness (roughly 4.36 avg Score).
  • Description: This cluster represents the most vulnerable nations. The data shows that these countries face a "double burden" of extremely low economic output and significantly lower Social Support (0.92) compared to the other groups.
  • Representative Countries: South Sudan, Afghanistan, Yemen, Central African Republic, and Pakistan.
  • Visual Location: Bottom-left corner of the chart, showing a dense concentration of countries struggling to break past the $5,000 GDP mark.

2. Cluster 2: The "Emerging" Middle (Green)

  • Profile: Middle Income (roughly $14,286 avg GDP) & Moderate Happiness (roughly 5.81 avg Score).
  • Description: This is the "transition" zone. Interestingly, while their average GDP is roughly 7x higher than the Struggling cluster, their Happiness Score jumps significantly by roughly 1.5 points. This group includes rapidly developing economies that have secured basic stability but have not yet reached elite wealth status.
  • Representative Countries: Brazil, China, Kazakhstan, Costa Rica, and Montenegro.
  • Visual Location: The steep "curve" of the graph. This cluster demonstrates the highest "marginal return" on wealthsmall increases in GDP here lead to massive gains in happiness.

3. Cluster 0: The "Thriving" Elite (Blue)

  • Profile: High Income (roughly $56,209 avg GDP) & High Happiness (roughly 7.02 avg Score).
  • Description: These nations score highest across every metric. However, the "diminishing returns" phenomenon is most visible here. Despite having 4x the GDP of the Emerging cluster ($56k vs $14k), their happiness score is only roughly 1.2 points higher. This suggests that beyond a certain threshold, extra wealth yields smaller improvements in well-being.
  • Representative Countries: Finland, United States, Germany, Austria, and Belgium.
  • Visual Location: The top-right plateau, where the curve flattens out.

4. Observations on Outliers (The "Happy Poor")

While the general trend indicates that higher GDP correlates with happiness, the clustering reveals important outliers that challenge this rule.

  • "Punching Above Their Weight": Some nations, such as Nicaragua, were assigned to the "Emerging" (Green) cluster despite having a GDP (roughly $1,958) that is typical of the "Struggling" (Orange) cluster.
  • Analysis: Nicaragua's high Happiness Score (6.105) allows it to defy its economic category. This suggests that for certain nations, strong performance in non-monetary metricssuch as Social Support or Freedomcan effectively compensate for lower economic output, allowing the population to achieve high well-being without high wealth.

Conclusion & Evaluation

1. Synthesis of Findings

This project set out to decode the primary drivers of global well-being by analyzing data from 156 nations. By integrating statistical profiles, regression modeling, and unsupervised clustering, we have derived the following insights:

A. The Global Landscape (Descriptive Statistics)

The world shows a moderate level of happiness with a global mean of 5.41 ($\sigma=1.11$). However, this average hides extreme disparities.

  • The Ceiling: Nordic nations, led by Finland (7.77), Denmark, and Norway, consistently set the benchmark for high well-being.
  • The Floor: Conflict-affected nations such as South Sudan (2.85) and the Central African Republic represent the lower bound, highlighting how instability devastates national mood.

B. The Economics of Happiness (Regression Analysis)

Through polynomial and logarithmic regression testing, we confirmed that the relationship between wealth (GDP) and happiness is non-linear.

  • Diminishing Returns: The Logarithmic Regression model provided the best fit with the lowest error (MSE: 0.364), outperforming linear models (MSE: 0.507).
  • Economic Interpretation: This confirms the "saturation effect." For developing nations (Cluster 1), small economic gains yield massive spikes in happiness. However, for the "Thriving Elite" (Cluster 0), adding more wealth yields progressively smaller returns in well-being.

C. The Pillars of Well-Being (Feature Significance)

Using Standardized Multivariate Regression, we isolated the impact of specific features independent of their scale. The model achieved an $R^2$ of 0.640, explaining nearly two-thirds of the variance in global scores.

  • Primary Driver: Surprisingly, Social Support (0.358) outperformed GDP per capita (0.289) as the strongest predictor of happiness.
  • Secondary Driver: Freedom to make life choices (0.237) and Internet Access (0.218) proved to be critical secondary pillars.
  • Insignificance: Contrary to expectations, Generosity and Perceptions of Corruption showed negligible direct impact on the overall score in this specific model.

D. Distinct Global Tiers (Clustering)

Using the Elbow Method, we determined that the world naturally segments into $K=3$ distinct clusters.

  1. Cluster 1 (Struggling): Low GDP (~\$2k) and low social support.
  2. Cluster 2 (Emerging): The "transition zone" where happiness rises sharply with moderate economic gains (~\$14k GDP).
  3. Cluster 0 (Thriving): The wealthy plateau (~\$56k GDP) where happiness scores stabilize near 7.0.

2. Evaluation & Limitations

While our analysis provides robust insights, the following limitations must be considered regarding the methodology and data integrity.

Data Processing & Imputation

  • Imputation Bias: To maintain a dataset of 156 countries, we utilized KNN (K-Nearest Neighbors) imputation to estimate missing values for "Education Expenditure." While this prevents data loss, it introduces synthetic data based on mathematical similarity rather than observed reality.
  • Label Inconsistencies: Significant effort was required to harmonize inconsistent country labels (e.g., "Congo (Kinshasa)" vs. "DRC"). While corrected, any remaining mismatches could exclude micro-states from the final merge.

Methodological Constraints

  • Correlation $\neq$ Causation: Our regression proves that Happiness and GDP move together, but it does not prove directionality. It is plausible that happier populations are more productive, creating a reverse causality loop.
  • Omitted Variable Bias: With an $R^2$ of 0.64, roughly 36% of the variance remains unexplained. Factors such as climate, political stability, mental health infrastructure, and cultural values (which are difficult to quantify) are missing from the model.

Metric Subjectivity

  • Self-Reporting Bias: The "Happiness Score" is subjective (Cantril Ladder). Cultural norms heavily influence these ratings; in some cultures, reporting extreme happiness is frowned upon, while in others, it is socially expected. This introduces a "cultural noise" that standardizing data cannot fully remove.
